article.description: Becky Hammon scored all of her 15 points on 3-pointers as the Liberty beat the Fever 70-62 Friday night to close within 2½ games of first-place Washington in the WNBA's Eastern Conference.
article.headline: Liberty close ground in East race
article.linkText: Liberty hold on after big early lead against Fever
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- New York Liberty coach Richie Adubato hopes his team won't fade in the season's stretch run the way they did in the second half against Indiana on Friday night. But just like in the Liberty's latest win, he's counting on them to have enough left to hold on. Becky Hammon scored all of her 15 points on 3-pointers as the Liberty beat the Fever 70-62 Friday night to close within 2½ games of first-place Washington in the WNBA's Eastern Conference. New York, which beat Los Angeles on Thursday, also has back-to-back games on Monday and Tuesday, causing Adubato some concern about his team's durability. "Every time we've got four games in six days it's rough on this team,'' he said. "I've got to use the bench, but I've got a young bench. I've got to hope my veterans can reach back and it seems they're able to do that.'' The Liberty (13-9) used a smothering full-court press in the first half to build a 19-point lead, before holding off a late Indiana rally. Indiana's Monica Maxwell scored consecutive baskets, her first two of the game, to make it 64-55 with 1:37 left. New York's Teresa Weatherspoon, a 51 percent free throw shooter, missed two attempts from the line and Maxwell capitalized. She made both of hers on the next possession as Indiana pulled within seven. Olympia Scott-Richardson was fouled by New York's Tari Phillips, her sixth foul, and converted both shots to make it 64-59. But the Liberty made four free throws in the final minute to seal the game. Tamika Whitmore scored 13 points and Vickie Johnson had 12 for New York, which won its third straight. Tamika Catchings led the Fever (8-13) with 21 points and 12 rebounds, while Scott-Richardson had 10 points. The Fever's loss was their fourth straight, a season high, and a playoff berth seems out of reach. "It's never over,'' Catchings said. "We need to come out and win. We can't afford to lose any more games. But it's never over.'' Indiana, which went without a field goal over the final 8½ minutes of the first half, found its touch early in the second. Catchings and Niele Ivey hit 3s during a 12-6 run as Indiana turned a 38-22 halftime deficit into a 10-point game. New York though, would never let the lead dip below 10 until Maxwell's baskets. New York made its first five 3-pointers, with Hammon hitting three and Crystal Robinson two. Hammon's total was one shy of the WNBA season high for 3s. The Liberty forced 12 turnovers in the first half. "We pressed them early to get the lead and get ahead,'' Adubato said. "Then you're gambling you'll run out of gas. So you have to judge if you'll get more positives than negatives. It got us a big enough lead that we could hold on.'' Robinson, Hammon and Johnson combined to shoot 9-for-12 from the field in the half.

Notes: Former heavyweight champion George Foreman was the honorary captain for the Fever. Foreman is in town to broadcast Saturday's WBC welterweight championship bout at Conseco Fieldhouse. Vernon Forrest will defend his title against Shane Mosley. ... The Fever are 2-4 on their eight-game homestand. They finish it this week with games against Charlotte and Minnesota. ... Indiana Pacers guard Ron Mercer was at the game. ... New York has an 8-1 career record against Indiana. ... New York is 3-0 on the back end of back-to-backs.
